[One can only hope that precious doses of the vaccine are not being given to individuals who are not on the frontline fighting Ebola. It certainly is important for international responders to be vaccinated.]

******
[4] Update summary
Date: Fri 18 May 2018
Source: STAT News [edited]
http://bit.ly/2rReOWu


The WHO is exploring whether experimental therapies might be used in the outbreak, with Salama revealing that the DRC government has been asked if it would permit emergency use of ZMapp, a treatment of monoclonal antibodies. Approval may be given, he said, but Salama cautioned that it would be difficult to use ZMapp at Bikoro, the epicenter of the outbreak, given the state of the medical infrastructure there. ZMapp must be given by infusion.

[Byline: Helen Branswell]

--
Communicated by:
ProMED-mail Rapporteur Mary Marshall

[Excellent summary that is recommended reading. The excerpt on ZMapp is included here to clarify it is therapeutic to be used after infection; it is not a vaccine. - MM]

