******
[7] Cost of response
Date: Fri 18 May 2018 1:15 PM
Source: Science magazine [edited]
http://www.sciencemag.org/news/2018/05/despite-spread-port-city-congo-ebola-outbreak-isn-t-international-emergency-yet-who


Peter Salama, who heads WHO's Health Emergencies Programme, said 2 shipments of the vaccine have already arrived in the DRC and as many as 10 000 people will be targeted to receive it, starting [Mon 21 May 2018]. Vaccine teams will offer shots to people who have come in contact with cases, their contacts, and so-called front-line responders, including medical staff, transport teams, and burial workers.

WHO says it needs USD 26 million to mount a response over the next 3 months; USD 9.3 million has already been committed from its own funds, governments, and nonprofits. Jeremy Farrar, who heads the Wellcome Trust in London -- which has promised to provide one-third of that initial commitment -- says the "swift and decisive" response and the small number of cases leads him to support the decision not to declare a PHEIC. "It is a fine judgment call and has to be kept under review," Farrar tells Science Insider. "Any suggestion of a deterioration and a PHEIC should be called."

Farrar stresses that a PHEIC has upsides and downsides. "PHEIC declarations do heighten awareness, engagement, and can free up funds, but there are some negative consequences," he says. "Often borders are closed, flights are stopped, trade comes to a standstill -- all of which can have negative consequences for the epidemic and the ability to bring it under control."

Robert Steffen [who heads the IHR Emergency Committee] told reporters that the current situation does not call for any restrictions on travel or trade but that departing passengers at DRC airports and in the ports of Mbandaka should be screened for fever. The DRC is surrounded by 9 countries; all should strengthen their surveillance and preparedness, Steffen said. "If the outbreak expands significantly or if there is international spread, the emergency committee will be reconvened and will reconsider its fundamental decision," he said.

[Byline: Jon Cohen]

--
